The rapid proliferation of large language models and agentic artificial intelligence (AI) has necessitated a fundamental re-evaluation of cognitive workflows. Traditionally, information-age processes relied on a linear progression of human-led research, drafting, and review. However, as the digital phase of technological evolution transitions into a delegation of cognition to algorithms, the risk of "cognitive merging" becomes acute. When a single AI system is tasked with framing an issue, researching facts, drafting a work product, and defending its own output, the resulting "one-stream" process often masks structural weaknesses, accelerates logic drift, and erodes the critical distance required for effective human decision-making. The LCES (Legal Calculus Educational System) sequence—Blueprint, Research, Construct, Challenge, Decide—emerges as a necessary framework for "procedural literacy," providing an adversarial, structured, and reviewable environment that restores the primacy of human judgment.   

The Evolution of Procedural Literacy and the Rationality of Computation
Procedural literacy, a term originally conceptualized within computer science and media theory, describes the ability to not only use technical tools but to understand, construct, and manage the underlying processes that govern them. In the early 1960s, Alan Perlis argued that programming and computational logic should be treated as a core component of a university education, equivalent in importance to mathematics and English in developing a student’s "rationality". Perlis defined rationality as fluency in the definition, manipulation, and communication of convenient structures, and he believed that the computer’s critical role lay in helping students develop an intuition for which problems are relevant.   

This historical perspective is essential for understanding the LCES framework. The goal of procedural literacy is "technical-cultural mastery," where the practitioner understands that writing and logic are not neutral skills but practices that shape how we perceive and interact with the world. As we delegate increasingly complex cognitive functions to AI, the risk of "deskilling"—the loss of embodied or tacit knowledge—becomes a structural failure rather than an individual one. The LCES sequence prevents this by treating technology as an "epistemic scaffold" that supports rather than replaces human reasoning.   

