The Psychological Dimension: Preventing "Middle Management" Syndrome
One of the most profound insights from current behavioral research is that mandated AI use can create "algorithmic cages"—standardized procedures that strip workers of agency over their own cognitive processes. When workers are held responsible for AI-generated output they did not truly "author," they feel reduced to "middle managers for their own thoughts". This is not merely a feeling but a structural result of "capacity-hostile environments" where the AI mediations impede the cultivation of human capacities.   

The LCES framework serves as a "capacity-friendly" environment. By forcing the human to lead the Blueprinting phase and making the final Decide, the framework ensures that the human remains the primary author of the work’s intent and conclusion. The AI agents handle the "middle management" of information retrieval and draft synthesis, but the Challenge phase forces the human to re-engage with the material as a critical judge.   

